341	/* This function is called every time we are going to transmit new data
342	 * to the client. The behavior is the following:
343	 *
344	 * If the client should receive new data (normal clients will) the function
345	 * returns C_OK, and make sure to install the write handler in our event
346	 * loop so that when the socket is writable new data gets written.
347	 *
348	 * If the client should not receive new data, because it is a fake client
349	 * (used to load AOF in memory), a master or because the setup of the write
350	 * handler failed, the function returns C_ERR.
351	 *
352	 * The function may return C_OK without actually installing the write
353	 * event handler in the following cases:
354	 *
355	 * 1) The event handler should already be installed since the output buffer
356	 *    already contains something.
357	 * 2) The client is a slave but not yet online, so we want to just accumulate
358	 *    writes in the buffer but not actually sending them yet.
359	 *
360	 * Typically gets called every time a reply is built, before adding more
361	 * data to the clients output buffers. If the function returns C_ERR no
362	 * data should be appended to the output buffers. */
363	int prepareClientToWrite(client *c) {
